{"title_page": "Charlie Barr", "text_new": "'''Charles Barr''' (11 July 1864 \u2013 24 January 1911), was an accomplished sailing skipper who three times captained winning [[America's Cup]] yachts.<ref name=\"barrobit\">{{cite news| url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1911/01/25/104818034.pdf| title=Capt Charles Barr, Noted Skipper, Dead| date=25 January 1911| format=pdf| newspaper=[[The New York Times]]| accessdate=2010-04-28}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nCharlie Barr was born in [[Gourock]], [[Scotland]] in 1864 and first apprenticed as a grocer before working as a commercial fisherman. In 1884, he took a job with his older brother John, delivering a sailing yacht, ''Clara'', to America. ''Clara's'' racing success was such that in 1887, John was selected to skipper the Scottish challenger, [[Thistle (yacht)|''Thistle'']], the representative of the [[Royal Clyde Yacht Club]]; Charlie served as a member of the crew. ''Thistle'' was soundly defeated by [[Volunteer (yacht)|''Volunteer'']]. In the process, however, the brothers Barr were introduced to [[Nathanael Herreshoff]], and Charlie Barr's yachting career was launched. Charlie Barr would sail Herreshoff designs for much of the rest of his professional sailing life.\n\n==America's Cup success==\nCaptain Charles Barr was skipper of the yacht ''[[Columbia (1899 yacht)|Columbia]]'' in 1899 and defeated [[Sir Thomas Lipton]]'s [[Shamrock (yacht)|''Shamrock'']]. Two years later, in 1901, Charlie Barr was again at the helm against a Lipton sponsored yacht, ''Shamrock II'', a {{convert|137|ft|abbr=on|adj=on}} [[George Lennox Watson|Watson]]-designed cutter. In 1903, Barr was the captain of the winning yacht [[Reliance (yacht)|''Reliance'']], one of the most famous racing yachts to be designed by Nathanael Herreshoff. Barr was inducted into the [[America's Cup Hall of Fame]] in 1993 and into the [[National Sailing Hall of Fame]] at San Diego yacht club, Point Loma, California, on 23 October 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://espn.go.com/olympics/sailing/story/_/id/7132035/dennis-conner-ted-turner-head-sailing-hall-fame-class| title=15 to enter sailing hall of fame| date=21 October 2011| agency=[[The Associated Press]]| accessdate=2012-09-02}}</ref>\n\n==Atlantic record==\nHe is best known for setting the [[Transatlantic sailing record|record for the fastest crossing by a sailing yacht of the Atlantic Ocean]] on the schooner [[Atlantic (yacht)|''Atlantic'']] in the 1905 Kaiser's Cup Transatlantic Race. Barr made his crossing in 12&nbsp;days, 4 hours, 1 minute, 19 seconds, an outright racing record that stood 75 years until [[Eric Tabarly]]'s 1980 crossing on his aluminium trimaran ''Paul Ricard''. Barr's [[monohull]] record stood for nearly 100 years until beaten in 1997 by the yacht ''[[Nicorette (1996 yacht)|Nicorette]]'' completing the crossing in 11 days 13 hours 22 minutes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sailspeedrecords.com/historical-list-of-offshore-world-records.html |title=Historical list of Offshore World Records |publisher=World Record Speed Sailing Council |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131129130934/http://www.sailspeedrecords.com/historical-list-of-offshore-world-records.html |archivedate=2013-11-29 }}</ref>\n\nBarr died whilst visiting [[Southampton]], England on 24 January 1911;<ref name=\"barrobit\"/> he is buried in [[Southampton Old Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Charles Barr |url=http://www.coss.org.uk/People-of-the-Town.php |work=Some personalities associated with Southampton |publisher=City of Southampton Society |accessdate=2011-09-25}}</ref>\n\nBarr was inducted into the [[National Sailing Hall of Fame]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nshof.org/inductees/barr-charlie/|title=Charlie Barr 2011 Inductee |publisher=Nshof.org |date= |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{citation|title=Charlie Barr - the story of a skipper supreme|author=Barry Pickthall|date=2013-07-18}} - [http://www.classicboat.co.uk/articles/charlie-barr-part-one-of-our-series-on-the-greatest-british-racing-skipper-of-them-all/ part 1], [http://www.classicboat.co.uk/articles/the-hero-at-the-helm/ part 2], [http://www.classicboat.co.uk/articles/charlie-barr-part-three-of-his-life-and-times/ part 3]\n*[https://www.herreshoff.org/achof/charlie_barr.html Charlie Barr, America's Cup Hall of Fame]\n*{{cite news |title=Captain Charlie Barr, Premier of Yachting Skippers |date=4 June 1905 |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1905/06/04/119118673.pdf |format=pdf |accessdate=2008-08-07}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barr, Charlie}}\n[[Category:America's Cup sailors]]\n[[Category:1864 births]]\n[[Category:1911 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:People from Gourock]]\n[[Category:Scottish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Scottish male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:19th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:19th-century American people]]\n[[Category:America's Cup Hall of Fame]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Inverclyde]]\n", "text_old": "'''Charles Barr''' (11 July 1864 \u2013 24 January 1911), was an accomplished sailing skipper who three times captained winning [[America's Cup]] yachts.<ref name=\"barrobit\">{{cite news| url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1911/01/25/104818034.pdf| title=Capt Charles Barr, Noted Skipper, Dead| date=25 January 1911| format=pdf| newspaper=[[The New York Times]]| accessdate=2010-04-28}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nCharlie Barr was born in [[Gourock]], [[Scotland]] in 1864 and first apprenticed as a grocer before working as a commercial fisherman. In 1884, he took a job with his older brother John, delivering a sailing yacht, ''Clara'', to America. ''Clara's'' racing success was such that in 1887, John was selected to skipper the Scottish challenger, [[Thistle (yacht)|''Thistle'']], the representative of the [[Royal Clyde Yacht Club]]; Charlie served as a member of the crew. ''Thistle'' was soundly defeated by [[Volunteer (yacht)|''Volunteer'']]. In the process, however, the brothers Barr were introduced to [[Nathanael Herreshoff]], and Charlie Barr's yachting career was launched. Charlie Barr would sail Herreshoff designs for much of the rest of his professional sailing life.\n\n==America's Cup success==\nCaptain Charles Barr was skipper of the yacht ''[[Columbia (1899 yacht)|Columbia]]'' in 1899 and defeated [[Sir Thomas Lipton]]'s [[Shamrock (yacht)|''Shamrock'']]. Two years later, in 1901, Charlie Barr was again at the helm against a Lipton sponsored yacht, ''Shamrock II'', a {{convert|137|ft|abbr=on|adj=on}} [[George Lennox Watson|Watson]]-designed cutter. In 1903, Barr was the captain of the winning yacht [[Reliance (yacht)|''Reliance'']], one of the most famous racing yachts to be designed by Nathanael Herreshoff. Barr was inducted into the [[America's Cup Hall of Fame]] in 1993 and into the National Sailing Hall of Fame at San Diego yacht club, Point Loma, California, on 23 October 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://espn.go.com/olympics/sailing/story/_/id/7132035/dennis-conner-ted-turner-head-sailing-hall-fame-class| title=15 to enter sailing hall of fame| date=21 October 2011| agency=[[The Associated Press]]| accessdate=2012-09-02}}</ref>\n\n==Atlantic record==\nHe is best known for setting the [[Transatlantic sailing record|record for the fastest crossing by a sailing yacht of the Atlantic Ocean]] on the schooner [[Atlantic (yacht)|''Atlantic'']] in the 1905 Kaiser's Cup Transatlantic Race. Barr made his crossing in 12&nbsp;days, 4 hours, 1 minute, 19 seconds, an outright racing record that stood 75 years until [[Eric Tabarly]]'s 1980 crossing on his aluminium trimaran ''Paul Ricard''. Barr's [[monohull]] record stood for nearly 100 years until beaten in 1997 by the yacht ''[[Nicorette (1996 yacht)|Nicorette]]'' completing the crossing in 11 days 13 hours 22 minutes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sailspeedrecords.com/historical-list-of-offshore-world-records.html |title=Historical list of Offshore World Records |publisher=World Record Speed Sailing Council |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131129130934/http://www.sailspeedrecords.com/historical-list-of-offshore-world-records.html |archivedate=2013-11-29 }}</ref>\n\nBarr died whilst visiting [[Southampton]], England on 24 January 1911;<ref name=\"barrobit\"/> he is buried in [[Southampton Old Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Charles Barr |url=http://www.coss.org.uk/People-of-the-Town.php |work=Some personalities associated with Southampton |publisher=City of Southampton Society |accessdate=2011-09-25}}</ref>\n\nBarr was inducted into the [[National Sailing Hall of Fame]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nshof.org/hall-of-fame/78-the-national-sailing-hall-of-fame/hall-of-fame-2011/320-barr-charlie-2011-hall-of-fame|title=Charlie Barr 2011 Inductee |publisher=Nshof.org |date= |accessdate=December 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{citation|title=Charlie Barr - the story of a skipper supreme|author=Barry Pickthall|date=2013-07-18}} - [http://www.classicboat.co.uk/articles/charlie-barr-part-one-of-our-series-on-the-greatest-british-racing-skipper-of-them-all/ part 1], [http://www.classicboat.co.uk/articles/the-hero-at-the-helm/ part 2], [http://www.classicboat.co.uk/articles/charlie-barr-part-three-of-his-life-and-times/ part 3]\n*[https://www.herreshoff.org/achof/charlie_barr.html Charlie Barr, America's Cup Hall of Fame]\n*{{cite news |title=Captain Charlie Barr, Premier of Yachting Skippers |date=4 June 1905 |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1905/06/04/119118673.pdf |format=pdf |accessdate=2008-08-07}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barr, Charlie}}\n[[Category:America's Cup sailors]]\n[[Category:1864 births]]\n[[Category:1911 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:People from Gourock]]\n[[Category:Scottish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Scottish male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:19th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:19th-century American people]]\n[[Category:America's Cup Hall of Fame]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Inverclyde]]\n", "name_user": "Cajohnson56", "label": "safe", "comment": "provided wiki link to NSHOF, corrected ref link to NSHOF induction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charlie_Barr"}
{"title_page": "Oscar Casares", "text_new": "{{for|the painter|Oscar Casares (painter)}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> \n| name          = Oscar Casares\n| image         = Oscar Casares 2019 Texas Book Festival.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = C\u00e1sares at the 2019 Texas Book Festival \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1964|05|07|mf=yes}} \n| birth_place   = [[Brownsville, Texas]]\n| occupation    = Author, Professor of Creative Writing\n| language      = English\n}}\n \n'''Oscar Casares''' (born May 7, 1964) is an American writer and an associate professor of creative writing.<ref>{{cite news | date=December 23, 2004 |  first=Evan | last=Smith | magazine=Texas Monthly | url=http://www.klru.org/texasmonthlytalks/archive/casares.php | title=Novelist Oscar Casares}}</ref> He is the author of ''[[Brownsville: Stories]]'' and ''[[Amigoland]]''. Casares teaches at the [[University of Texas at Austin]] where he is director of the Creative Writing Program.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/died-129888-superintendent-honored.html | title=Distinguished alumni announced | date=August 11, 2011 | newspaper=The Brownsville Herald}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\n*Guggenheim Fellowship (2020)\n*National Endowment for the Arts Fellowship (2006)\n*James A. Michener Award, Copernicus Society of America, Iowa Writers' Workshop (2002)<ref>{{cite news | title=The stories of his life | first=Sharyn | last=Wizda Vane | date=March 2, 2003 | newspaper=Austin American-Statesman }}</ref>\n*Dobie Paisano Fellowship, Texas Institute of Letters, University of Texas (2002)<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/books/2002-06-14/94965/ | title=The 2002-03 Dobie Paisano Fellows | first=Shawn | last=Badgley | date=June 14, 2002 | newspaper=Austin Chronicle}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n===Books===\n*''[[Where We Come From: a novel]]''  