{"title_page": "Frederic Thompson", "text_new": "{{Infobox person \n| name =Frederic Thompson\n | image = Frederic Thompson 001.jpg\n| caption = \n| birth_name = Frederic Williams Thompson\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1873|10|31}} \n| birth_place =[[Ironton, Ohio|Ironton, Ohio]], US\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1919|6|6|1873|10|31}} \n| death_place =[[Manhattan|Manhattan, New York]], US\n| resting_place = [[Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx, New York)|Woodlawn Cemetery]] in [[The Bronx,  New York]]\n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| residence =\n| nationality =\n| other_names =\n| known_for = [[showman]],  creator of large amusement parks\n| education = | employer = | occupation = | title = | salary = | networth = | height = \n| weight = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | religion = \n| spouse ={{marriage|[[Mabel Taliaferro]]|1906}}, {{marriage|Selene Wheat Pilcher|1913}}| partner = | children = | parents = \n| relatives = | signature = | website = | footnotes = }}\n\n'''Frederic Williams Thompson''' (October 31, 1873 &ndash; June 6, 1919) was an American architect, engineer, inventor, and [[showman]] known for creating amusement rides and one of the first large [[amusement park]]s.\n\n==Biography==\n\nFrederic Thompson was born in [[Ironton, Ohio|Ironton, Ohio]] on [[Halloween]] 1873. His father, Casey, moved the family around allot working as a manager in the steel industry in [[St. Louis|St. Louis, Missouri]], [[Johnstown, Pennsylvania]], [[Springfield, Illinois]] and [[Nashville, Tennessee]].<ref>Woody Register, The Kid of Coney Island: Fred Thompson and the Rise of American Amusements, Oxford University Press - 2003, page 27</ref> Frederic trained as an architectural draftsman. He had many jobs early on including salesman, draftsman, and even as an artist.<ref>Woody Register, The Kid of Coney Island: Fred Thompson and the Rise of American Amusements, Oxford University Press - 2003, page 39</ref> At age 19 or 20 he worked several jobs at the 1893 [[World\u2019s Columbian Exposition]] in Chicago and went on to participate at other expositions, including the 1901 [[Pan-American Exposition]] in [[Buffalo, New York]].\n\nAt the Pan-American Exposition Thompson teamed up with [[Elmer \"Skip\" Dundy]] to design and build an amusement ride called [[A Trip to the Moon (attraction)|A Trip to the Moon]]. They considered their ride a display of science and educational but the exposition organizers deemed it too fanciful and relegated it to the fair's [[Midway (fair)|midway]]. Tickets for the popular ride were [[U.S. dollar|US$]]0.50 (${{formatprice|{{Inflation|US|0.50|1901}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}) at the time, twice the price of other attractions at the exposition. It was experienced by over 400,000 people before it closed on November 2, 1901.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.westland.net/coneyisland/articles/lunapark.htm | title=Coney Island - Luna Park | date=May 1, 1998 | accessdate=April 24, 2012 | author=Stanton, Jeffrey}}</ref> It was the first electrically powered mechanical \"dark ride\" and one of the first space rides.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://io9.com/5914655/in-1901-you-could-pay-50-cents-to-ride-an-airship-to-the-moon | title=In 1901, you could pay 50 cents to ride an airship to the Moon | publisher=retro futurism | date=31 May 2012 | accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter the exposition, Thompson and Dundy moved the attraction to Tilyou's seaside [[Steeplechase Park]] on [[Coney Island]] in [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, New York]]. They went on to purchase the nearby [[Sea Lion Park]], vastly expanded it, and opened it in 1903 renamed [[Luna Park (Coney Island, 1903)|Luna Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gottaloveconeyisland.com/Luna_Park.html |title=Luna Park |publisher=GottaLoveConeyIslandDotCom |accessdate=April 24, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015142433/http://gottaloveconeyisland.com/Luna_Park.html |archivedate=October 15, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1905 Thompson and Dundy built a huge indoor stadium built in Manhattan called the [[New York Hippodrome|Hippodrome]]. In 1906 he married stage and silent-screen actress [[Mabel Taliaferro]].<ref>Woody Register, The Kid of Coney Island: Fred Thompson and the Rise of American Amusements, Oxford University Press - 2003, page 216</ref> He managed her in the 1907 Broadway play ''Polly of the Circus'',<ref>{{cite news |author= |title=Fred Thompson Marries. Head of Thompson & Dundy Weds Miss Mabel Taliaferro |url= |quote= |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=December 1, 1906 }}</ref> ''Springtime'' (1909) and the film ''Cinderella'' (1911).<ref>Woody Register, The Kid of Coney Island: Fred Thompson and the Rise of American Amusements, Oxford University Press - 2003, pages 216-217</ref> They had one child and were divorced in 1911.<ref>{{cite news |author= |title=Mabel Taliaferro Sues. Charges Her Husband, Fred Thompson, with Cruelty in Divorce Action |url= |quote= |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date= }}</ref> By 1912 Thompson\u2019s fortunes had turned, and he declared bankruptcy. In 1913 he married Selene Wheat Pilcher.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm9516711/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm Frederic Thompson, Biography, imdb.com]</ref> He suffered from [[alcoholism]] and [[Bright's disease]] and after surgery (one of many over a two year span) died in New York City on June 6, 1919 at the age of 45.<ref>Woody Register, The Kid of Coney Island: Fred Thompson and the Rise of American Amusements, Oxford University Press - 2003, page 299</ref><ref>[https://www.westland.net/coneyisland/articles/thompson&dundy.htm Jeffrey Stanton, Coney Island - Thompson & Dundy, 1998]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=CrZ1bY0CtWoC&dq=Frederic+Thompson+luna&source=gbs_navlinks_s The Kid of Coney Island: Fred Thompson and the Rise of American Amusements by Woody Register, Oxford University Press - 2003]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://nationalhumanitiescenter.org/pds/gilded/people/text2/thompson.pdf \u201cAmusing the Million\u201d by Frederic Thompson, EVERYBODY\u2019S MAGAZINE SEPTEMBER 1908]\n* [https://www.coneyislandhistory.org/hall-of-fame/fred-thompson Fred Thompson, Creator of Luna Park]\n* [https://www.westland.net/coneyisland/articles/thompson&dundy.htm Coney Island - Thompson & Dundy]\n* [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/7689997/frederic-thompson Frederic Thompson - find A Grave]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thompson, Frederic Williams}}\n[[Category:1873 births]]\n[[Category:1919 deaths]]\n[[Category:American entertainment industry businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Burials at Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American architects]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person \n| name =Frederic Thompson\n | image = Frederic Thompson 001.jpg\n| caption = \n| birth_name = Frederic Williams Thompson\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1873|10|31}} \n| birth_place =[[Ironton, Ohio|Ironton, Ohio]], US\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1919|6|6|1873|10|31}} \n| death_place =[[Manhattan|Manhattan, New York]], US\n| resting_place = [[Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx, New York)|Woodlawn Cemetery]] in [[The Bronx,  New York]]\n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| residence =\n| nationality =\n| other_names =\n| known_for = [[showman]],  creator of large amusement parks\n| education = | employer = | occupation = | title = | salary = | networth = | height = \n| weight = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | religion = \n| spouse ={{marriage|[[Mabel Taliaferro]]|1906}}, {{marriage|Selene Wheat Pilcher|1913}}| partner = | children = | parents = \n| relatives = | signature = | website = | footnotes = }}\n\n'''Frederic Williams Thompson''' (October 31, 1873 &ndash; June 6, 1919) was an American architect, engineer, inventor, and [[showman]] known for creating amusement rides and one of the first large [[amusement park]]s.\n\n==Biography==\n\nFrederic Thompson was born in [[Ironton, Ohio|Ironton, Ohio]] on [[Halloween]] 1873. His father, Casey, moved the family around allot working as a manager in the steel industry in [[St. Louis|St. Louis, Missouri]], [[Johnstown, Pennsylvania]], [[Springfield, Illinois]] and [[Nashville, Tennessee]].<ref>Woody Register, The Kid of Coney Island: Fred Thompson and the Rise of American Amusements, Oxford University Press - 2003, page 27</ref> Frederic trained as an architectural draftsman. He had many jobs early on including salesman, draftsman, and even as an artist.<ref>Woody Register, The Kid of Coney Island: Fred Thompson and the Rise of American Amusements, Oxford University Press - 2003, page 39</ref> At age 19 or 20 he worked several jobs at the 1893 [[World\u2019s Columbian Exposition]] in Chicago and went on to participate at other expositions, including the 1901 [[Pan-American Exposition]] in [[Buffalo, New York]].\n\nAt the Pan-American Exposition Thompson teamed up with [[Elmer \"Skip\" Dundy]] to design and build an amusement ride called [[A Trip to the Moon (attraction)|A Trip to the Moon]]. They considered their ride a display of science and educational but the exposition organizers deemed it to fanciful and relegated it to the fair's [[midway]]. Tickets for the popular ride were [[U.S. dollar|US$]]0.50 (${{formatprice|{{Inflation|US|0.50|1901}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}) at the time, twice the price of other attractions at the exposition. It was experienced by over 400,000 people before it closed on November 2, 1901.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.westland.net/coneyisland/articles/lunapark.htm | title=Coney Island - Luna Park | date=May 1, 1998 | accessdate=April 24, 2012 | author=Stanton, Jeffrey}}</ref> It was the first electrically powered mechanical \"dark ride\" and one of the first space rides.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://io9.com/5914655/in-1901-you-could-pay-50-cents-to-ride-an-airship-to-the-moon | title=In 1901, you could pay 50 cents to ride an airship to the Moon | publisher=retro futurism | date=31 May 2012 | accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter the exposition, Thompson and Dundy moved the attraction to Tilyou's seaside [[Steeplechase Park]] on [[Coney Island]] in [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, New York]]. They went on to purchase the nearby [[Sea Lion Park]], vastly expanded it, and opened it in 1903 renamed [[Luna Park (Coney Island, 1903)|Luna Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gottaloveconeyisland.com/Luna_Park.html |title=Luna Park |publisher=GottaLoveConeyIslandDotCom |accessdate=April 24, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015142433/http://gottaloveconeyisland.com/Luna_Park.html |archivedate=October 15, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1905 Thompson and Dundy built a huge indoor stadium built in Manhattan called the [[New York Hippodrome|Hippodrome]]. In 1906 he married stage and silent-screen actress [[Mabel Taliaferro]].<ref>Woody Register, The Kid of Coney Island: Fred Thompson and the Rise of American Amusements, Oxford University Press - 2003, page 216</ref> He managed her in the 1907 Broadway play ''Polly of the Circus'',<ref>{{cite news |author= |title=Fred Thompson Marries. Head of Thompson & Dundy Weds Miss Mabel Taliaferro |url= |quote= |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=December 1, 1906 }}</ref> ''Springtime'' (1909) and the film ''Cinderella'' (1911).<ref>Woody Register, The Kid of Coney Island: Fred Thompson and the Rise of American Amusements, Oxford University Press - 2003, pages 216-217</ref> They had one child and were divorced in 1911.<ref>{{cite news |author= |title=Mabel Taliaferro Sues. Charges Her Husband, Fred Thompson, with Cruelty in Divorce Action |url= |quote= |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date= }}</ref> By 1912 Thompson\u2019s fortunes had turned, and he declared bankruptcy. In 1913 he married Selene Wheat Pilcher.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm9516711/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm Frederic Thompson, Biography, imdb.com]</ref> He suffered from [[alcoholism]] and [[Bright's disease]] and after surgery (one of many over a two year span) died in New York City on June 6, 1919 at the age of 45.<ref>Woody Register, The Kid of Coney Island: Fred Thompson and the Rise of American Amusements, Oxford University Press - 2003, page 299</ref><ref>[https://www.westland.net/coneyisland/articles/thompson&dundy.htm Jeffrey Stanton, Coney Island - Thompson & Dundy, 1998]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=CrZ1bY0CtWoC&dq=Frederic+Thompson+luna&source=gbs_navlinks_s The Kid of Coney Island: Fred Thompson and the Rise of American Amusements by Woody Register, Oxford University Press - 2003]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://nationalhumanitiescenter.org/pds/gilded/people/text2/thompson.pdf \u201cAmusing the Million\u201d by Frederic Thompson, EVERYBODY\u2019S MAGAZINE SEPTEMBER 1908]\n* [https://www.coneyislandhistory.org/hall-of-fame/fred-thompson Fred Thompson, Creator of Luna Park]\n* [https://www.westland.net/coneyisland/articles/thompson&dundy.htm Coney Island - Thompson & Dundy]\n* [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/7689997/frederic-thompson Frederic Thompson - find A Grave]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thompson, Frederic Williams}}\n[[Category:1873 births]]\n[[Category:1919 deaths]]\n[[Category:American entertainment industry businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Burials at Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American architects]]\n", "name_user": "Fountains of Bryn Mawr", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frederic_Thompson"}
